				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Paulson Testifies That &#8216;Punitive&#8217; A.I.G. Terms Were Also Necessary</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Aaron M. Kessler			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-06T15:44:11+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 6, 2014 11:44 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 6, 2014 11:44 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/AIG/AIG-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/AIG/AIG-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/AIG/AIG-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003161324" width="592" height="395" alt="Former Treasury Secretary Henry M. Paulson Jr., center, leaving court after testifying in a suit brought by A.I.G.âs former chief."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Former Treasury Secretary Henry M. Paulson Jr., center, leaving court after testifying in a suit brought by A.I.G.âs former chief.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Drew Angerer for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/06/paulson-takes-the-stand-in-a-i-g-trial/" data-title="Paulson Testifies That &#8216;Punitive&#8217; A.I.G. Terms Were Also Necessary" data-description="Including hard terms for A.I.G. was politically necessary to getting the TARP program going, but Henry M. Paulson Jr. said he did support the bailout package and its terms.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/09/24/business/dealbook/aig-documents.html">Documents on A.I.G.</a></li>
<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/06/a-i-g-bailout-revisionists-version/">Andrew Ross Sorkin: A.I.G. Bailout, Revisionistsâ Version</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t20h25s" class="update">Updated, 8:25 p.m. | </span> <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/p/henry_m_jr_paulson/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Henry M. Paulson Jr.">Henry M. Paulson Jr.</a>, who was <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/t/treasury_department/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the U.S. Treasury Department.">Treasury</a> secretary when the government rescued the <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=AIG&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about American International Group Inc">American International Group</a>, said on Monday that a bankruptcy of the insurance giant would have been âcatastrophicâ for the economy, but acknowledged that the terms of the governmentâs bailout were âpunitive.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Paulson was the first of a series of witnesses who were leading government figures during the financial crisis in 2008 to testify in the trial of a lawsuit that challenges what became a $192 billion government rescue of A.I.G. He testified for little less than two hours on Monday morning under questioning from <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/david_boies/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about David Boies.">David Boies</a>, the lawyer representing <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/g/maurice_r_greenberg/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Maurice R. Greenberg.">Maurice R. Greenberg</a>, formerly chief executive of A.I.G., and lawyers from the Justice Department.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Greenberg, a major A.I.G. shareholder through his company Starr International, sued the government, contending that the rescue imposed illegally onerous terms. On behalf of A.I.G. shareholders, Mr. Greenberg is seeking more than $40 billion in compensation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Paulson testified on Monday that he believed the terms of A.I.G.âs bailout in September 2008 were âpunitiveâ and âharsherâ compared with the assistance other financial institutions received at the time. He said that political considerations played into the decision to apply âpunitiveâ terms to A.I.G.: It had become a lightning rod for public outrage that needed to be dealt with.</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/06/a-i-g-bailout-revisionists-version/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/Sorkin/Sorkin-thumbWide.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="A.I.G. Bailout, Revisionistsâ  Version" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/06/a-i-g-bailout-revisionists-version/?ref=dealbook">A.I.G. Bailout, Revisionistsâ  Version</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Maurice R. Greenberg, A.I.G.âs former chief and a large shareholder, has spun a ludicrous tale in court that the bailout of the insurer was unfair to its investors.</p>
			</div>
			
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When asked by Mr. Boies if it was important for the government bailout of A.I.G. to be seen as harsh to quell political opposition, Mr. Paulson said it was. The former Treasury secretary acknowledged he made that very point on Sept. 16, 2008 â the day the A.I.G. bailout was approved by the Federal Reserve â when he spoke with Barack Obama and <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/john_mccain/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about John McCain.">John McCain</a>, who were candidates for president at the time. Being able to explain that A.I.G. faced onerous terms was crucial to getting them to hold back on criticism, Mr. Paulson said. The same was true with congressional leaders, he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But despite the tough conditions, Mr. Paulson said he âsupported the terms of the loan,â and favored the governmentâs action to save A.I.G.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Asked by Mr. Boies whether he believed an A.I.G. collapse would have wreaked havoc on the American people, Mr. Paulson responded, âI sure did, yes.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/dbpix-aig3/dbpix-aig3-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/dbpix-aig3/dbpix-aig3-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/business/dbpix-aig3/dbpix-aig3-blog480.jpg" id="100000003160290" width="480" height="320" alt="Henry M. Paulson Jr., left, a former Treasury Secretary, at the United States Court of Federal Claims in Washington on Monday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Henry M. Paulson Jr., left, a former Treasury Secretary, at the United States Court of Federal Claims in Washington on Monday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Drew Angerer for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The governmentâs lawyers also scored points in their brief examination of Mr. Paulson on Monday, focusing their efforts on how precarious A.I.G.âs position was even after the initial September bailout. By the end of October, Mr. Paulson testified, A.I.G. was on the verge of bankruptcy once again â and faced a ratings downgrade that would have required additional capital that the company did not have. âThe situation had deteriorated,â Mr. Paulson said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a result, the Treasury Department decided to tap its authority to its then-new bailout fund, known as the Troubled Asset Relief Program, to infuse A.I.G. with another $40 billion in taxpayer cash. Mr. Paulson said he felt it was a necessary decision, but one he feared could blow up in Treasuryâs face. At the time, Congress had approved the $700 billion TARP legislation, but had only authorized half of that, $350 billion to be spent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI was worried that $40 billion into A.I.G. would so enrage the public and Congress that we might not get the last $350 billion,â Mr. Paulson said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As to whether there were other alternatives to the public bailout of A.I.G., Mr. Paulson played down that possibility. He was asked by Mr. Boies about the potential for the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/china_investment_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the China Investment Corporation.">China Investment Corporation</a>, Chinaâs sovereign wealth fund, to rescue A.I.G. during the critical period in September, and said he did not believe the Chinese would ever have made a deal that did not involve United States government assurances or backstops, which the Treasury Department was unwilling to provide at the time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI was 100 percent certain the Chinese werenât going to come in,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Paulson was on the stand a shorter time than anticipated. It was so fast, in fact, that the next scheduled witness, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/g/timothy_f_geithner/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Timothy F. Geithner.">Timothy F. Geithner</a>, Mr. Paulsonâs successor as Treasury secretary, was still in New York, the governmentâs lawyers said on Monday. Another witness was substituted for him Monday afternoon, and Mr. Geithner will be on the stand Tuesday morning, the lawyers said.</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/23/as-ex-chief-of-a-i-g-sues-u-s-wall-st-is-happy-to-pay-the-tab/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/24/business/jpAIG/jpAIG-thumbWide.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Wall St. Bankrolls Ex-Executive as He Sues Over A.I.G. Bailout" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/23/as-ex-chief-of-a-i-g-sues-u-s-wall-st-is-happy-to-pay-the-tab/?ref=dealbook">Wall St. Bankrolls Ex-Executive as He Sues Over A.I.G. Bailout</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By BEN PROTESS and AARON M. KESSLER</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Maurice R. Greenberg, the former chief of A.I.G., has now raised several million dollars from three Wall Street investors to help cover the cost of the case.</p>
			</div>
			
